title: "University reform and the productivity of researchers"
collection: publications
category: wp
abstract: ' In this paper, I empirically study the effect of administrative autonomy on the productivity of public sector institutions.
I take the 2007 French university reform as a case study of administrative reorganisation of a public system and decompose its components to assess their different effects. The context allows me to distinguish the effect of administrative autonomy to universities, competition for grants, and mergers into larger institutions while keeping rigid funding schemes relatively stable. Using bibliometric data, I first compare mobility flows in treated institutions for each treatment to those in never-treated institutions. I then compare the quantity and quality of publications of researchers affiliated at treated institutions and researchers affiliated at never-treated institutions. I find that administrative autonomy itself, when not coupled with reforms in funding, does not lead to higher attractiveness of French universities either in France or the rest of the world, and causes negative effects on research quality of French researchers, leading to a drop of about 6\% in citations. Conversely, university mergers lead to an increase in arrivals of researchers from abroad of 18\%. Receiving a competitive grant and merging into a larger university also improves the productivity of their employees, but not sufficiently to offset the effect of administrative reorganisation. Simply allowing public institutions to compete in terms of output and hiring but not for funding does not improve efficiency.'
